The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a pamphlet
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually old, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn back" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the town.
"Men rarely suffer such a sin."
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help with labor and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state, Burkina Faso is occupied in a special residence of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information brochure that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns the newspaper Die Standard of the disadvantages of writing awareness.
Witchcraft accusations are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, neighbouring Burkina Faso, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman got caught in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It set on fire when the group wanted to "drive out evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of “witches” is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"The Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen from the Gambian peoples to the president's property in Kanilai," the report said.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a pocima of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the detainees did not survive their stay on the estate.
After international pressure, they finally released about a thousand detainees.
