Architects have understood that offices also need nursery
The administrative building Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to her.
Architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio came numerous well-known buildings from Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-guardianship.
At the company, around 90 people work, mostly at the age of the baby boom, and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits offered by Arch.Design to its workers as part of its social program.
Constructors and architects in this way have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-guardianship was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of the management, managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-guardianship is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme on Human Resources and Employment, as well as the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a provision of more than 2.8 million CZK) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), Arch.Design is obliged to keep the mini-gardenhouse running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted a year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the submission of the funding application.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff. In addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The daycare currently hosts children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-guardian", it can accommodate only a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The functioning of the daycare is flexible to accommodate the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the daycare, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-curriculum programme are comparable to the usual preschool curriculum.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class has not only toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up kids from school late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the signed companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of personnel.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, locals dubbed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of the scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and wildlife.
Paying more attention, we observe a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door ornaments, lookouts and signposts.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gracia, emerged from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project adornments emerged for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration on Casa Batlló’s proposals was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and Gaudí’s Park Güell, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones" shortly after its completion.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the central heating season with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the building rules of the time and was not influenced by them.
Still, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the city hall was so impacted with the result that it requested it to be corrected.
He was annoyed, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, rather the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council’s request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors was installed the owner himself.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase leading up to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can thus communicate seamlessly, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was based simply on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house you will find the most spacious and recharged apartment of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded visits to the common area and attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other buildings of Gaudí in the city.
