The army has enough wicks to surround the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to ignite explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the lifespan of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the wick for explosives from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES by justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnics of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is decided however that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives each year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want exemptions, neither the Minister of Defense Alexandr Vondr nor the captain of the army Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could the army be justified in spending sixty kilometers of wick.
This length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
If so, the army would have enough stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the engineers or special units) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
Soldiers in the Rapid Intervention Brigade personally complained to Minister Vondra recently because they said they barely had ammunition for various weapons, so even shooting practices were limited for money.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also can't understand that we are repeatedly bought such amounts of wick."
“But it’s their decision and they’ll undoubtedly know why they act like that.”
"For us, the army is a good customer that we, as a company, try to satisfy," admits the commercial director of STV Group, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>cký.
Ministry of Defense spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick, saying he will also have stocks of this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>cký, of STV Group, indicates that the wick only has a shelf life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, two years.
"If stored in perfect condition, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
At the end of its service life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, when buying 445 kilometers of wick, it got a discount.
“They cost us 60 percent less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defence’s shopping centre.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of the pyrotechnics of the police, which eliminate the munitions of World War II or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its useful life runs out.
It was decided for safety reasons for pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of wick can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of 200,000 people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: we will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
