The increase in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 more kroner per year than it is now.
However, the main electricity suppliers lowered prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaic, has increased.
However, the gas becomes moderately expensive, especially at the time when heating is used more and therefore, the higher the consumption.
In this case, they must also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive across the country, the price change of central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about 50 more crowns per month for central heating since January, while families in Liberec will pay more than 1,000 more crowns per year.
Prague residents will also have to endure a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially in the event that the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rental does not vary, the Pragues will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will continue to be among the lowest in the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will increase by 7.4%.
