This is the two-seater version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The three remaining aircraft are the single-seater L-159.
These are still preserved in Aer Vodochody and the sales intermediary, the company Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peje<0xC5><0xA1>k of the defense press department says it is not yet known when the planes will be physically withdrawn from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seater aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, with no investments or additional contributions from the Ministry."
“The two-seater L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state,” he told Právo Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek.
He added that the army is not running out of two-seater aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for the amount of 200 million crowns for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new aircraft has already been received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, EADS pledged that the aircraft will be added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that the EADS company is the one that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve for the practice of pilots from NATO countries."
"Therefore, it is up to the buyer to decide how he will use them in this framework," Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek says.
The newspaper Hospodá<0xC5><0x99>ské noviny published beforehand that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159s.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defense did not call a tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense management claims that the exchange promotes future export of L-159 overseas.
The Czech army acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already denounced the Czech Ministry of Defence to the European Court of Justice because it should choose aircraft by making a European tender and not by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last is expected to arrive at Kbely airport in Prague within fourteen days.
