As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin made his way into a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the female members of Chengguan, the corpulent police officers of the urban order of China, feared and despised for their whimsical energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Sign up!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How beautiful the girls are!"
Four girls who barely went through adolescence wearing white gloves and identical olive-green jackets and tight pants to get attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed on top of the hair tied with blue and white stripes.
“Personally, I think they have a normal appearance,” Mr. Tang said, dismissively.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a purportedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a disco snack cart, and watched it with a frown constantly for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, expressly elected by their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s minimal respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors from Hubei Province beat a passer-by to death after using his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a waste dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a quarrel with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available to download online, introduces Chinese-trained inspectors who attack street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded “really meticulous cleaning.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district solicited eight new female recruits through a notice in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered whether women had real duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district’s notice called for female candidates aged 18 to 22, with a good figure “and the five harmonious facial features.”
