"Very routine."
One reason is that female officers lack the power of their male counterparts to confiscate merchandise from vendors.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male supervisors.
This tends to protect them from the sudden public demonstrations of animosity against bureaucracy, which are common everywhere in China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the provincial capital of Yunnan, mutined after the false rumor spread that some Chengguan officers had killed a vendor.
More than a dozen police officers or Chengguan officers were injured in the night episode; 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
At the moment Xindu has avoided such violence.
