Prosecutors will not bring charges against Senator Ensign
The senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have excused Senator John Ensign from criminal charges arising from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure lobbying work for the woman’s husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said it was "certainly pleased" with the decision, which came after a full-year investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of his investigation and that he has no plans to bring charges against him on this matter."
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign might have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobbying.
The interviews, email and other documents first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, obtain lucrative work through lobbying, to achieve silence for Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as a treasurer for an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find work for Mr. Hampton and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under law from lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called “revolving door lobbying ban,” which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, “it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared cautious in accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop the prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens, amid procedural misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s top lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to raise charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to prosecutors.
“I’m not comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we thought they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got work through lobbying thanks to Ensign’s help to Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him that he was "scraping" the Interior Ministry on a disputed issue.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and called the transportation secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When news of the affair first appeared last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told reporters that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign spokesman Jennifer Cooper announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said the senator expected the ethics committee to quickly follow the Justice Department’s lead and conclude its investigation.
“Senator Ensign wishes to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada,” he said.
Cheshire appeal will target Twitter
There were half a dozen of them "chatting" in the rows of the courtroom.
Minute by minute, they sent reports of the appalling testimony via Twitter.
In the end, the defense says, there were more than 140,000 Twitter messages about the process that addressed the rape and the children tied to their beds in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the largely-followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of a Cheshire, Connecticut family, is set to reach an official end, with the imposition of the death penalty judge voted by the jury.
But Mr. Hayes’ lawyers have filed court papers outlining the arguments of appeals that are likely to occupy the courts for years.
One of the most provocative claims that intense reports about the process, including widespread use of Twitter by mass media journalists, created “an atmosphere of circus,” and such widespread and immediate saturation with exhilarating details caused public passions to exert an inappropriate influence on the jury.
The claim could force appeal judges to deal with the question of whether the new technology requires new rules in the courtroom.
“Based on what I experienced during this trial, I think there is a real danger that the inclusion of the new technology in the courtroom is affecting the individual’s rights to a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, senior defense attorney for Mr. Hayes.
Trial judge Jon C. Blue of the State High Court laconically rejected the lawsuits in a ruling last week, saying that the news media were “carefully controlled” and that there was no evidence that the jury was led by the passion.
But it will probably not be the last word on the subject.
For decades, appeals courts have recognized that celebrity case coverage can raise questions about the impartiality of a lawsuit.
In a historic 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in his ruling, in the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
The crime is believed to have been inspired by the television show and the film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers said the appeals courts that examined Mr. Hayes’ conviction half a century later might be intrigued by the argument that new rules might be needed to control the way of communication from the courtrooms, something unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There is a general cause for concern about the impact of new media” on high-profile processes, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford School of Law, who studied Connecticut’s death penalty and wrote a report saying it was arbitrarily imposed.
Professor Donohue said some appeal judges might be intrigued by the idea that limiting immediate communication from courtrooms could make the trials fairer.
The Twitter issue is just one of many of the issues outlined by Hayes’ lawyers, which will likely be discussed for years, delaying an execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes may have been harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jury members, showing them creepy photographs of the crime scene during the jury selection.
Jurors have said they were horrified by the photographs of the victims, 48-year-old Jennifer Hawke-Petit, and her daughters, 17-year-old Hayley and 11-year-old Michaela.
Defense lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his bizarre decision to order the jury to deliberate over a weekend.
The jury was not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process may attract most of the interest.
They noted in a rejection of the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continually threw firewood into the fire of excitement over the case.
“The daily crowding of tweets from the media, cameras and reporters outside the courtroom,” the lawyers wrote, “was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps throughout the state.”
His attention to Tweeter coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said the complaint that immediate news was more important than reports delivered more slowly was a ludicrous view that would make the court’s policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said appeals courts were often drawn to arguments about the adaptation that was required in courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In their letter, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which revokes Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to the coverage of the trial, and made it clear that they would demand that the new media would require new rules.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents the Sheppard vs. Maxwell case of the 21st century.”
Can civicism build a bridge to unite divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, this week has unleashed a bit of civicism in Washington.
Is it a foreshadowing of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a swift return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and Congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But as they all say, it was at least a courteous discussion about the differences of the two sides, as well as an acknowledgment of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to earn partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilized, despite political differences remaining among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates the members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Now both sides are in a trial period, probe each other to identify signs of cooperativism and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That is why the meeting on Tuesday and subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too great and too deeply rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed with respect to how things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions, which then become extinct.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Likewise, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make them believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s White House meeting, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will reverse the situation to a confrontational one,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civicism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises of cutting state spending and overturning the new health law.
Those partisan lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include reform of the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting expenditures.
Co-Chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, forcibly introduced the issue of deficit to the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise on fiscal issues.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the Republicans in the White House and those in Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of party clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and medical care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would the change bring about?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the bias of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as it happened in 1995, then both parties will watch carefully the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will likely change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
Leaked U.S. document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a “cleptocracy,” leaving a portion of the bribes and protection money that it collects directly from the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in February.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service are handling huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called “vertical authority,” takes its share as money rises on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on its website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of cleansing since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who owns a major construction company, have systematically denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several libel lawsuits over such allegations.
In September, when he was asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested it was corrupt, he said: “It’s madness, it’s a scam, it’s an annoyance.”
According to the polls, the Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, since they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
“The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it ‘dysfunctional’, and to claim that the government functions more as a kleptocracy than as a government,” the statement said.
“Criminal elements enjoy a ‘krysha’ (a term from the criminal and mafia world that literally means ‘roof’ or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the office of the prosecutor, as well as all sectors of the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
Analysts identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow.
"Luzhkov is at the top."
“The SFS, the MVD and the militia are at the second level.”
“Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a void in some areas, because the city does not provide some services.”
The report states that the SFS collects money from larger companies, and that police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, “explained that Moscow commercial owners understand that it is best to get protection from the MVD and SFS (rather than organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but they are also protected by law.”
“For this reason, protection from criminal gangs is no longer a priority.”
The note notes that while the collection of money is complete, protection can be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly find their businesses closed for one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that he has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking suitcases, probably full of cash, inside the Kremlin itself.
“In his fight against corruption, Medvedev has to rely on the bureaucrats,” Georgy Satarov, director of the Indem expert group in Moscow, said in a recent interview.
“But he’s a part of this bureaucracy.”
“He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion a year.
In a recent survey on global perceptions of corruption conducted by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked 154 (countries are ranked from the least to the most corrupt).
The revelation of the U.S. Embassy’s note, which did not happen until late in the evening Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov may be blamed for Moscow’s weaknesses, it could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested the WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation that claimed U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this relates to our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policies in this country," he said.
“But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it was done in such an immoral way.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a dimly lit concrete classroom, with stained and peeled walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader and cared about his people,” said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as "the Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer Rouge government, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer Rouge fortress in northwestern Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former Khmer Rouge soldiers still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, long-standing loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations-Cambodia mixed court issued the first sentence of a former Khmer Rouge member, sentenced the former head of the well-known Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng, complicating reconciliation efforts and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among former Khmer Rouge, but they can do nothing,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent organization investigating the regime.
For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil.
“This is creating divisions within families.”
During the Khmer Rouge government of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of starvation, illness or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the government led by Pol Pot, the remnants of the regime and its military fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and jungles of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began to defect to the government, culminating in the surrenders of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 while awaiting the trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the oldest Khmer Rouge fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few Khmer Rouge elite officials retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the low-level soldiers remain poor and unqualified farmers.
“These people have gotten few benefits after the surrender,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which offers public forums across Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They have incorporated the utopian agrarian ideology of the regime.”
"They were raised without any concept of doing business."
Sr. Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before devoting himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
“Life with the Khmer Rouge was fine,” he said.
"Ta Mok gave everyone food."
“But now life is difficult because we have to self-sufficiency.”
The current Khmer Rouge court has also raised concerns here.
Earlier next year, the court is expected to begin prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister.
The court’s mandate is to prosecute the top leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will prosecute cases in addition to those four.
This did not serve much to soothe fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on Im Chaem, 64, who was a district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer Rouge rule in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told investigators at the Cambodia Documentation Center that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
During a recent shameful afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his home on wooden piles on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun cast long shadows on the dry grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rouge.
She said that if the court called her, she would not appear.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
“If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
“Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is precisely what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Chhang Youk of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces,” he said.
“It is our duty to gather these broken pieces together so that we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Rouge, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s high school history textbook, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little detail about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city's link to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their story.
But his parents reacted skeptically when he brought the book home to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court,” he said.
“They have suspicions because they are not sure about how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Khmer Rouge retains a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a pathway with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a black soot rectangle covered by an oxidized tin roof.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a mobile phone seller on the roadside, said he didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
“But he has a strong spirit and many locals go there to pray to him,” he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last break, where he would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in the hope of good luck.
