Red Bull triumphs in F1 with a Siemens secret weapon
A software designs improvements in cars in real time.
Since Red Bull broke into the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select universe of speed has been marked by surprise and success.
At first no one took into consideration the options of a newly arrived team and, despite the upward trajectory of the last seasons, last November, in the final line of the championship, everyone bet on Fernando Alonso’s Ferrari victory.
Without underestimating the driver’s skill of the final champion, German Sebastian Vettel, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that powers his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the “secret weapon” that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to make him a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far from high-end motor racing.
Called PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to design assembly lines of manufacturing plants worldwide, power plants, high precision instruments.
The goal is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding failures and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan’s most celebrated utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory has enabled Red Bull to design and carry out "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during races and in trials.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on his team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
Today, the Red Bull team employs 180 young, highly qualified professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the bolides.
The Siemens CEO explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull’s cars except the engine, which is Renault’s sole responsibility.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation of this craziness of technological improvement is the figure of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate the competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its cars in a town about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered “high secret.”
The staff for this task amounts to 580 people, including his two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull Formula 1 hero, no doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drinks brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, are other protagonists whose competition is invaluable and its notoriety is null.
Steve Nevey, head of technology at the factory, said five years ago it could be said that R&D advances in truck cars contributed 50% of the wins and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and the technology adds up to 85% of the success, while the drivers contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing as they are "unpredictable gladiators".
