Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro, but has set the conditions for the entire Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a dual government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or suppression of the 426 euros of aid to the unemployed without benefit, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Go ahead that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany begins to speculate about the three possible exits from the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although now seems like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budget strictness, fines to the transgressing countries, possible suspensions of payments from some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government took a constitutional reform out of its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed needed to be done (plans for fiscal rigor and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended Greece’s rescue decision.
It was already the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and published opinion were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding reform of the EU treaties, to make it possible to save a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved, and in the coming months we should be attending the process of reform of the Union that will make those measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which he may not agree very much, from that date onwards the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which infringer countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves on hold of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the years of the boom, will simply not tolerate it.
The enthusiasm is clear.
And we'd be wrong not to understand it.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they demand is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquility.
And let us take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood it this way and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that order must be put at home has been paved the way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t seem to be moving.
And, among the possibilities envisaged, the possibility of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with inserious countries cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Fraud Law
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos before Ajax show ingenuity but no willingness to escape a sanction.
The alleged expulsion by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the Nov. 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink flows to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsporting and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the match (which their team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time to draw fault paths to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned team coach José Mourinho with two games and with different financial amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten but followed rules of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the reported case is because it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (who in his anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and has sometimes fined his players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds another episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud by law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sporting regulation, but they seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of harm they cause to the sportsmanship.
One of the assets that the sports spirit comprises is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these assets that fair play is alluded to is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly exploiting the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradoxical thing about the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the penalty, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional offences examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the opponent is not placed in a disadvantageous situation or profit is made in the same game, since obviously the result of the action involves leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, since the team can be eliminated at the first change, and in addition with this performance the players meet a penalty game and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, from going through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions are not against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor to get the most out of what the rules allow.
In the present case, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without evading the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the boundary between wit and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of wit.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises by two factors: because it was about two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
