The peculiarity of the Pakistani nuclear program — that the weapons are not assembled but remain stored by components to make it difficult to destroy them in the event of an attack — is one of the main reasons for awakening in Washington.
The ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists it in a pre-visit report by then-National Security Adviser James Jones: “The proximity of some nuclear facilities to Taliban-attacked territory, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of transport of atomic materials.”
