However, it made clear that China will not change its objectives, but will continue to work together with the international community on this issue.
He noted that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity-building; institution-building; and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including last year’s passing of a new Energy Law, which sets out the targets set for reducing gas emissions, he explained.
In China, federal authorities have been working in a coordinated manner with state and local authorities to achieve energy saving, energy efficient use and emission reduction goals.
In addition, various multi-year plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, were abundant, underway or have already been completed.
For example, he said, the Energy Efficient Use Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and received investment from the United Nations (UN), government and private initiative.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for changing incandescent spots for savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, scientific adviser to the country’s government on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than is generally thought.
For example, he explained, per capita greenhouse gas emissions in China are six tonnes per person, while in the United States it is 100 tonnes; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
