I am changing the rules to get a visa.
Individuals should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview at the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time will be lower.
As of January 10, 2011, you will change the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates.
With the new procedure, most applicants will need to go to Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASCs) prior to their interview at the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section, will stay in the Consular Section less time than in the past.
Similarly, those who apply for visas at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visum-FAQs.html
