A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to virtually a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of specific major projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, are replaced by fluorescent compact bulbs or, better still, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or “LED”), much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate them.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the global fleet’s emissions.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of that amount should be further decreased to stabilize, before 2020, the rise in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluorescent light bulbs, the energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, the energy consumption is further reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average between 6,000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, allowing us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
A number of experts have expressed reservations about fluorescent light bulbs, as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report notes, the main source of mercury emission on the planet are not fluorocompact bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is wasted with incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of this international programme for each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save $1 billion a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it $2.5 billion.
