Avengers Hackers and Diligent Spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” US revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual habits only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long given ideas to cabaret artists to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news of public knowledge is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats exactly what had been written in previous works (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rosicrucian).
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for novelties about the non-existent), but because those who engage in occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as is lazy (or has little craving) the head of the secret services (if it could not be, I do know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the US embassy from Rome to the State Department was the same as Newsweek published the week before.
Then why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they say only what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of State can call each other on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer who watches research movies knows it perfectly, we just seem like we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad picture of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secretive secrets of the world’s most powerful country greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the " executioners".
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
In the days of Orwell, all power could be conceived as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power endure that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but yes, and a lot, to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the network, since it would be like posting it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it is also clear that, with current technologies, one cannot expect to keep confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has traveled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How can they maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned from memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: ultimately, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph (telephone).
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of the assembly, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travels it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to lead us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was secretly planned in the embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's chap in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked funding pledges (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been honoured.
And the French chapuzas have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged to contribute €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast-start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it really is worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, which puts it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without detriment to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what “new and additional” means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonization, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Nowadays, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, it does not refer to the expenditure of previous years or the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease), while pretending to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds...
Another crucial element is the sharing between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often emission reduction projects that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document for your own eyes.
It is the only country in the Union that so frequently uses the loan.
Germany uses it 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments to 100% of donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is making a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as it had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has taken care of the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other Member States going to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term minutiae in relation to the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is indispensable to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could push forward the debates on the stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently being debated): we will not get rid of the issue of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on other issues.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
