The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value given the limited number of samples analyzed, but they are illustrative of the problem addressed," acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that usually consume a child about ten years old in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, including 42 classified as possible or likely carcinogens and five classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PEs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“While, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for individual chemicals are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that consumers’ exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE pollutants is worrying,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were dressed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritive" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk generated by these “pollutant cocktails” to the consumer “is probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the seriousness of the situation" to implement a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 are in cereals.
